,Recommended,290970,14607033,"Posted: 22 February, 2015",all,ElleWolfe,"I really enjoy this game, it's addictive in a strange, perfectionist, control-freak sort of way. I love city builders but was looking for some a little more simple than a huge sim-city type deal and without the combat that other strategy games have. I never get bored with the diverse scenarios each map brings and the acheivements you can obtain.I have had no major gameplay issues, and have no serious complaints. As far as suggestions may go, I was hoping for a little more financial control, rather than really just balancing the wage-rent ratio. It gets a little annoying having to manually go in and sell my products every 10 seconds, whereas it would seem like a nice addition to offer contracts to the other cities in the same way you sometimes get from completeing commissions- every month a certain number of resources is sent over automatically.Also, the population(?) advisor lady gets on my nerves, it seems like people in every city want to expand insanely quicker than your set up or ready to handle regardless of the scenario. Obviously people in a vineyard paradise are going to demand nice things, but in small mining town scenarios people begin to demand luxuries that are not availiable for that map (cobbler, tailor, etc) and end up throwing a hissy fit and leaving. That sort of control of expansion and growth seems  like it would be nice to have as the mayor. It seems unrealistic that during this time period a small mining outpost would attract the rich, family-type crowd.On the opposite end of the spectrum I have had issues with houses refusing the expand even though the conditions are met, but I have no idea if that is part of the game considering they were the first few houses I built and subsequent houses did expand quickly.And one tiny thing that just upsets my OCD personality, is that you cannot rotate buildings. In my opinion, its the simple details that sets a game apart from a city-builder farming phone game. Even from the screen shots you see building stacked in clusters behind and infront of each other. This is a game that can boast time-period accuracy, but the concept of anyone, anytime moving into town and opening up a shoestore that directly blocks your front porch seems unlikely. It's purely an aesthetic annoyance, but seemed worth a mention.Overall though, seriously I love this game. And it takes some serious willpower to walk away even for a second."
